<subSubSection pageId="57" pageNumber="58" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
12. 
<taxonomicName LSID="B478830A-0823-5A45-8F73-D0FBFB875C0A" authority="Miq., Fl. Nederl. Ind. 1 (1): 150 (1855), emend. nov. J. Compton &amp; Schrire" authorityName="Miq., Fl. Nederl. Ind. 1 (1): 150" authorityYear="1855" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Padbruggea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Padbruggea" order="Fabales" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Streptophyta" rank="genus">Padbruggea Miq., Fl. Nederl. Ind. 1(1): 150 (1855), emend. nov. J.Compton &amp; Schrire</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="57" pageNumber="58" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
<taxonomicName authority="Miq., 1855" authorityName="Miq., Fl. Nederl. Ind. 1 (1): 150" authorityYear="1855" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Padbruggea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Padbruggea" order="Fabales" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Streptophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Padbruggea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has robust panicles with the peduncle and lateral axes densely brown velutinous (vs. robust panicles with peduncle and lateral axes finely grey-pubescent in 
<taxonomicName authority="J.Compton &amp; B.D.Schrire, 2019" authorityName="J. Compton &amp; Schrire" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Austrocallerya" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Austrocallerya" order="Fabales" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Austrocallerya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="Miq., 1855" authorityName="Miq., Fl. Nederl. Ind. 1 (1): 150" authorityYear="1855" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Padbruggea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Padbruggea" order="Fabales" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Streptophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Padbruggea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has inflated, 4.5-11 cm wide, oblong or obovoid coarsely ridged fruits (vs. inflated, 3-5.2 cm wide, fusiform, finely ridged or striate and torulose pods in 
<taxonomicName authority="J.Compton &amp; B.D.Schrire, 2019" authorityName="J. Compton &amp; Schrire" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Austrocallerya" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Austrocallerya" order="Fabales" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Austrocallerya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="J.Compton &amp; B.D.Schrire, 2019" authorityName="J. Compton &amp; Schrire" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Austrocallerya" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Austrocallerya" order="Fabales" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Austrocallerya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has arching type callosities on the standard petals vs. large papillate callosities in 
<taxonomicName authority="Miq. &amp; Fl.Nederl.Ind." authorityName="Craib, Fl. Siam. 1: 397" authorityYear="1928" baseAuthorityName="Dunn" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Padbruggea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Padbruggea filipes" order="Fabales" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="filipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Padbruggea filipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or ridge type callosities in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. dasyphylla" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" rank="species" species="dasyphylla">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">P. dasyphylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. maingayi" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" rank="species" species="maingayi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">P. maingayi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Miq., 1855" authorityName="Miq., Fl. Nederl. Ind. 1 (1): 150" authorityYear="1855" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Padbruggea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Padbruggea" order="Fabales" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Streptophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Padbruggea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed from southern China, IndoChina, Indonesia, Malaysia, Thailand to Myanmar whereas 
<taxonomicName authority="J.Compton &amp; B.D.Schrire, 2019" authorityName="J. Compton &amp; Schrire" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Austrocallerya" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Austrocallerya" order="Fabales" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Austrocallerya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in Australia, New Guinea, and some of the adjacent Pacific islands as far south as New Caledonia and Norfolk Island.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="57" pageNumber="58" type="type species">
<paragraph pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Type species.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
<taxonomicName authority="Miq., 1855" authorityName="Miq., Fl. Ned. Ind. 1 (1): 150" authorityYear="1855" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Padbruggea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Padbruggea dasyphylla" order="Fabales" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Streptophyta" rank="species" species="dasyphylla">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Padbruggea dasyphylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Miq.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="57" pageNumber="58" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Genus description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
Scrambling climbers reaching 15-25 m. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Stems</emphasis>
dark green becoming brown, terete, densely brown pubescent when young, glabrescent. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Leaves</emphasis>
with 9-19 leaflets, evergreen, pubescent above and below when young, glabrescent or sparsely pubescent at maturity, imparipinnate, rachis 10-30 cm long. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Stipules</emphasis>
1-8 mm long, ovate or lanceolate, caducous, pubescent or sericeous externally, glabrous internally. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Stipels</emphasis>
1-3 mm long, filiform, glabrous or setaceous (absent in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. filipes" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" rank="species" species="filipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">P. filipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Leaflets</emphasis>
5-12 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-3 cm, oblong, ovate or elliptic, apex acute or acuminate, margins glabrous or ciliate, base rounded or obtuse. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Inflorescence</emphasis>
an erect terminal, sometimes leafy or cauliflorous panicle 7-35 cm long, peduncle silvery or brown tomentose. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Flowers</emphasis>
13-25 mm long, emerging from April - June (July - August 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. filipes" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" rank="species" species="filipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">P. filipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Floral bracts</emphasis>
5-25 mm long, linear-lanceolate, ovate or cupuliform, apex acute to acuminate, densely pubescent externally and internally, margin ciliate, green, (pink or purple in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. filipes" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" rank="species" species="filipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">P. filipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), caducous. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Bracteoles</emphasis>
3-6 mm long, narrowly lanceolate, caducous (linear 1 mm long 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. filipes" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" rank="species" species="filipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">P. filipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Pedicels</emphasis>
4-7 mm long, densely pubescent (15-25 mm long, sericeous in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. filipes" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" rank="species" species="filipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">P. filipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Calyx</emphasis>
4-5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5 mm campanulate, green or purple, sericeous externally, glabrous internally, five lobed, teeth acute 1-6 mm long, margins ciliate. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Standard</emphasis>
14-25 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
14-22 mm, orbicular, inner surface lilac or pinkish, nectar guide yellow, back of standard pubescent, apex emarginate, callosities of ridge type (papillate in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. filipes" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" rank="species" species="filipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">P. filipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Wing petals</emphasis>
13-20 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
8-11 mm, violet or pinkish, slightly falcate, glabrous, more or less equal in length to the keel, elliptic, apex rounded, basal claw 4-5 mm long. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Keel petals</emphasis>
10-15 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-10 mm, white, densely hairy along lower margin externally (glabrous in 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. filipes" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" rank="species" species="filipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">P. filipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); navicular, claw 3-10 mm long, apex acute or rounded. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Stamens</emphasis>
diadelphous, nine fused together, the vexillary one free, all curved upwards at apex, glabrous. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Ovary</emphasis>
densely pubescent or sericeous, style 3-4 mm long, glabrous, tufted at base, curved upwards at apex, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">stigma</emphasis>
punctate. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Pods</emphasis>
10-25 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-11 cm, inflated, obovoid, compressed-cuboid or oblong, dehiscent, surface coarsely ridged to rugose, velutinous, subseptate. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Seeds</emphasis>
1-2, elliptic-ovoid or prolate-spheroid, 50-80 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
40-45 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
30-45 mm, hilum strap-shaped 16-36 mm long.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
